What I'm trying to get at is that an esp especially with EMG's but even with passive pickups like duncans or dimarzios don't quite resonate the way that other guitars do. You can't hear pick noises or natural harmonics quite as well, they don't buzz or have any uniqueness to them. So for me, I've switched to basically a les paul style guitar with p90s because I can go from really heavy tones to almost clean by just changing my picking dynamics, and I get a ton of pick noise, natural harmonics, and feedback. I also went from preferring low action high speed low drag to high action just cause it makes you put that little bit more effort into your playing that comes through on a recording. It's like the difference between listening to eddie van halen who played on a partscaster with high action and satriani. There's a certain grit that comes with a playing a guitar that isn't as easy to play.

>https://soundcloud.com/thegravenimages/3-what-you-want-to-see
listening right now. love shoegaze, and love the vibe you're going for.
a couple of notes
1st thing, for sure, it sounds like it couldn't use some background ambience. Not sure if you have that in already, because I can't hear it. Turn it up so it's audible, that's allowed in shoegaze
2nd thing I get that it's shoegaze, but it sounds to me like the guitar is mixed a little loud.
3rd thing - for some reason, during the breakdown that happens around 2:30, i would love to see you fuck with the time on some delay or reverb (pic related)

I'm listening to the full album now and it seems like the background ambience is the biggest thing that would add some pop.

Also, I notice you are layering your vocals with intent to add emphasis at certain points. Keep in mind that pretty much every recorded song you've heard in the past 50 years has AT LEAST 2-3 layers of vocals on the main vocals. 90s shoegaze really played around with this a lot, with tons and tons of vocal layers, often that didn't line up each other, to give that delay/reverb dreamy effect.

for reference, and to blatantly shill myself some more, here's a shoegaze-y song I did. I used 5 vocal layers on this track AND a light poly-chorus on top of that, plus reverb and delay.
https://soundcloud.com/my-american-dream/slip-away-2

overall though your vibe is strong and I know people that would really dig what you're doing. keep it up.

pic related, screenshot of the reverb swell I used on Agent of Chaos at the start of the drop, as reference for what I think you should do in the breakdown of the song you linked.

com:
Theodor Adorno hated jazz.

He thought that its repetitive chord structures were too easily commodified, too easy to use as brainwashing for the capitalist Culture Industry. The works he preferred, as a dichotomy with his loathed jazz, was modernist composition, specifically at times citing the compositions of Schoenberg. This music insists on attention, education, and is too strange to a mass audience's ears to be commodified. Modernist compositions are inherently academic exercises attempting to expand the language of music itself, rather than truly meant to be listened to.

Adorno was right about one thing, however: desires are always conditioned from somewhere, and he was right to say that capital was rapidly becoming our primary cultural conditioner. His point was Confucius-esque: if we all must learn, why not let our men of high culture teach? Having been raised well into the neoliberal imperial period, my teacher is and always has been the Top 40, which is the most condensed version of the standardization and repetition in music that Adorno feared. Play him a Max Martin song and he'd probably off himself.

The reason she's not breaking the guitar, is for the fact that she's holding it in the middle. Which takes away a lot of potential force. You want to hold poles on one end, which then puts all the power on the other end. Holding it in the middle balances the power out.

Because rock, even when it was at it's peaks of popularity like hair metal, grunge, nu metal, pop punk, etc has always been an "alternative" to the greater pop scene. It was always SOMEWHAT for the weird crowd, always somewhat geared toward an aspect of nicheness even when it was hugest. Why does that matter or have to do with file sharing you ask?

Because, think of it this way. You're a record company, you have no plans of leaving the music business, this is your bread and butter, the only thing you know and you've never planned for anything else in live and probably still are fairly rich, but you now realize the money you make has been cut into a quarter of what it once was. The first thing you're going to do, is cut out the "fat" whatever that may be, and focus only on A. the stuff that brings in the absolute biggest bucks and has the MOST mass appeal across borders (pop music) and B. focus on the stuff that is popular but maybe a little more niche but is cheapest to produce and put on tour en masse (rap music). Rock bands just aren't worth it to major labels these days to promote. Also, notice how exactly the timeline lines up for when rock bands stopped being promoted by major labels and also the phenomenon of popstars and rappers starting to be dressed like rockers and marketed towards "outsider" demographics? It's no coincidence, the labels are attempting to make up for the loss they knew they took by drawing as much of the rock crowd into these other things they can.

Nothing that is big in mainstream music is incidental, it all comes down to major labels investing in them and promoting them, you have exceptions to the rule here and there, but generally, it's all about how big of a billboard you can buy.

A letter by Wagner to Wesendonck:
>I recognize now that the characteristic fabric of my music (always of course in the closest association with the poetic design), which my friends now regard as so new and so significant, owes its construction above all to the extreme sensitivity which guides me in the direction of mediating and providing an intimate bond between all the different moments of transition that separate the extremes of mood. I should now like to call my most delicate and profound art the art of transition [(Übergang, also translated to as "crossing," and always relates to being between two points)], for the whole fabric of my art is made up of such transitions: all that is abrupt and sudden is now repugnant to me; it is often unavoidable and necessary, but even then it may not occur unless the mood has been clearly prepared in advance so that the suddenness of the transition appears to come as a matter of course. My greatest masterpiece in the art of the most delicate and gradual transition is without doubt the great scene in the second act of Tristan and Isolde. The opening of this scene presents a life overflowing with all the most violent emotions — its ending the most solemn and heartfelt longing for death. These are the pillars: and now you see, child, how I have joined these pillars together, and how the one of them leads over into the other. This, after all, is the secret of my musical form, which, in its unity and clarity over an expanse that encompasses every detail, I may be bold enough to claim has never before been dreamt of. If only you knew how that guiding emotion has inspired me to invent musical devices that would never have occurred to me previously (devices in terms of rhythm, as well as harmonic and melodic development), you would realize that even in the most specialized branches of art no truth is ever invented that does not derive from such grand primary motives. That, then, is art!

name: Anonymous
com:
>>101524082
Don't go too fast. It's tempting to play proper compositions immediately because you might already well be able to play the correct notes, but you won't learn to play it musically and will also hinder your progress on sight-reading significantly (you will be just memorizing them painstakingly).
Go slow and buy some good beginner's book and stick to really really simple pieces first. After a while you can mix in pieces from the Anna Magdalena book, Bartok's "for children" etc. but keep on playing the simple pieces from the beginner's book. If you can't make these simple pieces sound clean and musical you won't be able to do it for more difficult stuff.

As a zoomer who grew up with, and have been using spotify all my life and recently moved over to downloading and listening to my music locally. I think my biggest problem with it is that it incentivizes a lazy, consumerist approach to music.

Spotify has an extensive library, but it's still a library. If you rely on spotify as your main music source you don't have nearly the same freedom as someone who just downloads. This is especially a problem if you have an interest in foreign music or lo-fi / homerecording artist.

>But i just download the albums that are not there
This is a thing you can do but i still feel it limits the way you look at and explore music. I know back when i used spotify i would see an album i want to listen to, realize it's not on spotify and then just not listen to it because it'd be a hassle to find a link and i could just hear something on spotify instead. And even if i DID download an album i would rarely listen to it even if i liked it because the fact that it wasn't in the app was inconvenient.

It inherently reigns your taste in to the perimiters of an (expansive) gallery for the sake of convinience.

Secondly, i think the algorythmization and playlist centered nature of the app leads to some pretty lame ways to discover music and often keeps you floating around in entry-level territory pretty much forever. This can be supplemented by using other sources for music discovery, /mu/, rym, Last.fm. etc. but this usually completely leaves out any historical context, or idea of what ''scene'' a band was a part of. Instead of a work of art with a certain history and place in the musical landscape it just becomes ''artist similar to x'' or ''3.1 rated Indie rock, Powerpop, Punk rock album''
There is nothing wrong with listening to music this way but it's certainly more shallow and leaves you with bad idea of influences and the like..

But most of all organizing and curating my own personal music library is alot of fun.

>>101536493
If we're talking classic big band composers and old pop songwriters, it's simply for a change of mood or color like in Classical -- classic example, many of Ellington's bridges are just a 1-6-2-5 in some disparate key (Sentimental Mood, Darn That Dream, Sophisticated Lady, many such cases). Bridges of course are the most common place to do this because they're meant to be a switch-up. Modulating up by a 4th is most common (Sunny Side of the Street, A Train, Miss Jones (however briefly it alights upon the 4th lol), etc.)

When talking bebop and beyond, generally I wouldn't say there's so much a logic behind key changes in that sense. It's just about crafting a novel melody and chord sequence.

Also could be noted: bebop started out mostly as contrafacts of pop tunes. Beboppers would take those more basic changes and "jazzify" them so that they conformed more to the logic of jazz -- basically making everything they could into a 2-5 of some sort. Think of it like "streamlining" -- it would make comping and soloing easier because things would be more interchangeable. This often meant changing color chords like diminished chords into ii-Vs (for example, the A-7 to D7 in bars 3-4 of Groovin' High, originally simply a Ebdim in Whispering). While this would give the impression of the key having changed, really, it's just an extrapolated color chord, or passing chords of sorts. Sometimes these passing chords would become somewhat long digressions because the predicament was created of returning, in a functional manner, to the "actual" key.

Later when people started writing their own compositions in "the bebop style", they took these practices and made them an essential tenet of the compositions themselves. The digressions became even longer and the changes more frenetic.

Hope that helps answer your question.
